They are very smart.

14:25.000 --> 14:27.000
They watch the lecturers

14:27.000 --> 14:28.000
have a seminar in the law school every day,

14:28.000 --> 14:29.000
and they will kill each other.

14:29.000 --> 14:31.000
They watch Huashan's paper every day

14:31.000 --> 14:33.000
and become a big family.

14:34.000 --> 14:37.000
After they return to China,

14:37.000 --> 14:39.000
they can be a Ph.D.

14:39.000 --> 14:40.000
and teach law in Taiwan.

14:40.000 --> 14:42.000
But in the US Department of Law,

14:42.000 --> 14:44.000
you can hardly see any teachers

14:44.000 --> 14:45.000
who are JSD.

14:45.000 --> 14:46.000
Because they are

14:46.000 --> 14:48.000
Ph.D. for foreigners.

14:48.000 --> 14:50.000
This is a brief introduction.

14:50.000 --> 14:53.000
I used to think that

14:53.000 --> 14:55.000
if I went to the US to study law,

14:55.000 --> 14:57.000
I could just study LLM and JSD.

14:57.000 --> 14:58.000
But I thought,

14:58.000 --> 14:59.000
no,

14:59.000 --> 15:00.000
I want to try to

15:00.000 --> 15:01.000
receive the same training as Americans.

15:01.000 --> 15:03.000
If Americans want to become a professor of law,

15:03.000 --> 15:05.000
I will become a professor of law.

15:05.000 --> 15:07.000
So I started with Ph.D.

15:07.000 --> 15:08.000
Later,

15:08.000 --> 15:09.000
in my senior year,

15:09.000 --> 15:11.000
I will see if I can get a J.D.

15:11.000 --> 15:12.000
and try to find a job

15:12.000 --> 15:14.000
in the US Department of Law.

15:17.000 --> 15:19.000
Next, I will answer a question.

15:19.000 --> 15:21.000
What is history?

15:21.000 --> 15:22.000
I am often asked this question.

15:22.000 --> 15:24.000
But I think this is a disaster question.

15:24.000 --> 15:25.000
It's like I want to ask,

15:25.000 --> 15:27.000
what is physics?

15:27.000 --> 15:29.000
What is math?

15:29.000 --> 15:31.000
It is difficult to define a subject.

15:31.000 --> 15:33.000
But I think I can try

15:33.000 --> 15:35.000
to look at this subject

15:35.000 --> 15:37.000
from a more specific perspective.

15:37.000 --> 15:39.000
What is it?

15:39.000 --> 15:41.000
I think from the perspective of abstract theory,

15:41.000 --> 15:43.000
in the Western context,

15:43.000 --> 15:48.000
history is also a method of philosophy.

15:48.000 --> 15:49.000
In other words,

15:49.000 --> 15:50.000
the research we do in history

15:50.000 --> 15:52.000
is the same as asking a question,

15:52.000 --> 15:54.000
giving it a false hypothesis,

15:54.000 --> 15:57.000
and then verifying it, right?

15:57.000 --> 16:02.000
It is the same as philosophy, physics, and chemistry.

16:02.000 --> 16:04.000
We need to ask a question,

16:04.000 --> 16:07.000
and then use some methods to answer it,

16:07.000 --> 16:11.000
to verify if your hypothesis is correct.

16:11.000 --> 16:13.000
Of course, this is a bit of nonsense.

16:13.000 --> 16:15.000
Because anyone who studies Ph.D.

16:15.000 --> 16:17.000
has to do this kind of study.

16:17.000 --> 16:19.000
So I think we can look at history

16:19.000 --> 16:21.000
from a different perspective.

16:21.000 --> 16:25.000
Whether it is Greece or China,

16:25.000 --> 16:27.000
people in ancient times

16:27.000 --> 16:29.000
have a cycle of history.

16:29.000 --> 16:31.000
By cycle of history,

16:31.000 --> 16:33.000
I mean that

16:33.000 --> 16:35.000
for them,

16:35.000 --> 16:37.000
history is something that

16:37.000 --> 16:39.000
happens over and over again.

16:39.000 --> 16:41.000
For example,

16:41.000 --> 16:43.000
in the Tang Dynasty,

16:43.000 --> 16:45.000
Emperor Taizong said that

16:45.000 --> 16:47.000
history is the key to understanding the mind.

16:47.000 --> 16:49.000
In other words,

16:49.000 --> 16:51.000
as long as you study the past,

16:51.000 --> 16:53.000
you will learn some lessons.

16:54.000 --> 16:56.000
By cycle of history,

16:56.000 --> 16:58.000
I mean that

16:58.000 --> 17:00.000
there is nothing new under the sun.

17:00.000 --> 17:02.000
So I understand the past,

17:02.000 --> 17:04.000
and I understand the future.

17:04.000 --> 17:06.000
Because what happened in the past

17:06.000 --> 17:08.000
will keep happening over and over again.

17:08.000 --> 17:10.000
So as long as I know the past,

17:10.000 --> 17:12.000
I will know how to face the same thing in the future.

17:12.000 --> 17:14.000
What should I do when it happens again?

17:14.000 --> 17:16.000
But as we all know,

17:16.000 --> 17:18.000
this is a kind of fantasy.

17:18.000 --> 17:20.000
How is it possible that

17:20.000 --> 17:22.000
people 200 years ago

17:22.000 --> 17:24.000
would face the same problems

17:24.000 --> 17:26.000
as we do now?

17:26.000 --> 17:28.000
Of course, it is different.

17:28.000 --> 17:30.000
In the 18th and 19th centuries,

17:30.000 --> 17:32.000
history was taken over by the state.

17:32.000 --> 17:34.000
There was a very

17:34.000 --> 17:36.000
purposeful approach

17:36.000 --> 17:38.000
to help

17:38.000 --> 17:40.000
build a democratic country.

17:40.000 --> 17:42.000
For example,

17:42.000 --> 17:44.000
when Germany was about to be unified,

17:44.000 --> 17:46.000
a group of historians came out

17:46.000 --> 17:48.000
and wrote history of Germany.

17:48.000 --> 17:50.000
They told us that we were different

17:50.000 --> 17:52.000
from the Italians.

17:52.000 --> 17:54.000
We have a glorious history.

17:54.000 --> 17:56.000
Who is German?

17:56.000 --> 17:58.000
We have a common memory.

17:58.000 --> 18:00.000
This also happened

18:00.000 --> 18:02.000
in the end of the Qing Dynasty

18:02.000 --> 18:04.000
and the beginning of the Republic of China.

18:04.000 --> 18:06.000
Chinese historians told you

18:06.000 --> 18:08.000
that we are all descendants of the Yan Emperor.

18:08.000 --> 18:10.000
So we have a common ancestor.

18:10.000 --> 18:12.000
We must agree that we are all Chinese.

18:12.000 --> 18:14.000
So for a while,

18:14.000 --> 18:16.000
history was used by the state

18:16.000 --> 18:18.000
to build the common memory of the nation.

18:20.000 --> 18:22.000
In the 19th century,

18:22.000 --> 18:24.000
there was another trend.

18:24.000 --> 18:26.000
Social science,

18:26.000 --> 18:28.000
political science,

18:28.000 --> 18:30.000
and other social sciences

18:30.000 --> 18:32.000
wanted to become

18:32.000 --> 18:34.000
like natural science

18:34.000 --> 18:36.000
and discover the common principles

18:36.000 --> 18:38.000
of human society.

18:38.000 --> 18:40.000
They wanted to analyze

18:40.000 --> 18:42.000
why the French Revolution happened,

18:42.000 --> 18:44.000
what its causal relationship was,

18:44.000 --> 18:46.000
and what its social background conditions were.

18:46.000 --> 18:48.000
If we can build

18:48.000 --> 18:50.000
a abstract theory

18:50.000 --> 18:52.000
that the French Revolution

18:52.000 --> 18:54.000
will happen

18:54.000 --> 18:56.000
when the four conditions

18:56.000 --> 18:58.000
are met,

18:58.000 --> 19:00.000
we can predict

19:00.000 --> 19:02.000
when the next revolution will happen

19:02.000 --> 19:04.000
or prevent it from happening.

19:04.000 --> 19:06.000
Another famous example

19:06.000 --> 19:08.000
is Marx.

19:08.000 --> 19:10.000
He said that human history

19:10.000 --> 19:12.000
has a process.

19:12.000 --> 19:14.000
We will go from feudalism

19:14.000 --> 19:16.000
to a small class revolution

19:16.000 --> 19:18.000
to a large class revolution.

19:18.000 --> 19:20.000
Many historians' work

19:20.000 --> 19:22.000
is to prove

19:22.000 --> 19:24.000
the theory of social science

19:24.000 --> 19:26.000
and the process

19:26.000 --> 19:28.000
of social science principles.

19:28.000 --> 19:30.000
Until now,

19:30.000 --> 19:32.000
many historians in mainland China

19:32.000 --> 19:34.000
are still trying to prove

19:34.000 --> 19:36.000
the process of Marxism

19:36.000 --> 19:38.000
in China.

19:38.000 --> 19:40.000
This is the purpose

19:40.000 --> 19:42.000
of the third kind of history.

19:42.000 --> 19:44.000
The fourth kind of history

19:44.000 --> 19:46.000
is similar to the second kind of history,

19:46.000 --> 19:48.000
but it starts to ask smaller questions.

19:48.000 --> 19:50.000
Historians want to

19:50.000 --> 19:52.000
understand the history of the past

19:52.000 --> 19:54.000
and develop quantitative studies

19:54.000 --> 19:56.000
of economics or politics.

19:58.000 --> 20:00.000
The most famous example

20:00.000 --> 20:02.000
is Professor Daniel Clerman

20:02.000 --> 20:04.000
at the University of South Carolina.

20:04.000 --> 20:06.000
He taught at the University of Chicago

20:06.000 --> 20:08.000
because his wife was a lawyer

20:08.000 --> 20:10.000
who was afraid of the cold.

20:10.000 --> 20:12.000
His family moved to South Carolina.

20:12.000 --> 20:14.000
He is a history doctor

20:14.000 --> 20:16.000
and a law professor

20:16.000 --> 20:18.000
at the University of Chicago.

20:18.000 --> 20:20.000
His research is very interesting.

20:20.000 --> 20:22.000
He uses the documents

20:22.000 --> 20:24.000
and information

20:24.000 --> 20:26.000
he discovered

20:26.000 --> 20:28.000
in history training

20:28.000 --> 20:30.000
and his strong

20:30.000 --> 20:32.000
statistical and quantitative background

20:32.000 --> 20:34.000
to do some

20:34.000 --> 20:36.000
theoretical practical research.

20:36.000 --> 20:38.000
Some questions

20:38.000 --> 20:40.000
are difficult to answer.

20:40.000 --> 20:42.000
Does judicial independence

20:42.000 --> 20:44.000
help economic development?

20:44.000 --> 20:46.000
We are not like natural science,

20:46.000 --> 20:48.000
which can control all variables

20:48.000 --> 20:50.000
in the laboratory.

20:50.000 --> 20:52.000
When we want to study this topic,

20:52.000 --> 20:54.000
we have to do some social experiment

20:54.000 --> 20:56.000
to do the cause-and-effect theory,

20:56.000 --> 20:58.000
and we need to find

20:58.000 --> 21:00.000
a lot of agent variables.

21:00.000 --> 21:02.000
Every time a country

21:02.000 --> 21:04.000
does judicial independence reform,

21:04.000 --> 21:06.000
it often follows

21:06.000 --> 21:08.000
many other reforms at the same time.

21:08.000 --> 21:10.000
This is the best way

21:10.000 --> 21:12.000
to understand the relationship

21:12.000 --> 21:14.000
between judicial independence

21:14.000 --> 21:16.000
and economic development in the UK.

21:16.000 --> 21:18.000
Professor Dan Clearman

21:18.000 --> 21:20.000
has some very good information.

21:20.000 --> 21:22.000
For example,

21:22.000 --> 21:24.000
he found that

21:24.000 --> 21:26.000
in the 18th and 19th centuries,

21:26.000 --> 21:28.000
the UK was doing judicial independence reform.

21:28.000 --> 21:30.000
At the same time,

21:30.000 --> 21:32.000
East India Company

21:32.000 --> 21:34.000
was listed

21:34.000 --> 21:36.000
in London Stock Exchange

21:36.000 --> 21:38.000
because

21:38.000 --> 21:40.000
there was no

21:40.000 --> 21:42.000
good information transmission system.

21:42.000 --> 21:44.000
Therefore, news from London

21:44.000 --> 21:46.000
had to wait three or five days

21:46.000 --> 21:48.000
before it could be sent to Amsterdam.

21:48.000 --> 21:50.000
He thought

21:50.000 --> 21:52.000
that the agent variables

21:52.000 --> 21:54.000
of economic development

21:54.000 --> 21:56.000
were the high and low prices

21:56.000 --> 21:58.000
of East India Company's shares.

21:58.000 --> 22:00.000
Whenever a judicial independence

22:00.000 --> 22:02.000
law or reform

22:02.000 --> 22:04.000
occurred in the UK,

22:04.000 --> 22:06.000
East India Company's shares

22:06.000 --> 22:08.000
would rise or fall

22:08.000 --> 22:10.000
when the news

22:10.000 --> 22:12.000
was sent to Amsterdam.

22:12.000 --> 22:14.000
He used statistics

22:14.000 --> 22:16.000
to infer the situation in the UK.

22:16.000 --> 22:18.000
In the end,

22:18.000 --> 22:20.000
he concluded that

22:20.000 --> 22:22.000
every judicial independence reform

22:22.000 --> 22:24.000
in the UK

22:24.000 --> 22:26.000
had something to do

22:26.000 --> 22:28.000
with the rise of

22:28.000 --> 22:30.000
East India Company's shares.

22:30.000 --> 22:32.000
Without historical training,

22:32.000 --> 22:34.000
East India Company's shares

22:34.000 --> 22:36.000
would not have risen.

22:36.000 --> 22:38.000
This is another theory.

22:38.000 --> 22:40.000
In the early years,

22:40.000 --> 22:42.000
there was a theory

22:42.000 --> 22:44.000
that asked

22:44.000 --> 22:46.000
why there was

22:46.000 --> 22:48.000
no China in the West.

22:48.000 --> 22:50.000
In the early years,

22:50.000 --> 22:52.000
historians liked to ask

22:52.000 --> 22:54.000
why there was no capitalism in China,

22:54.000 --> 22:56.000
why there was no scientific revolution in China,

22:56.000 --> 22:58.000
and why there was no

22:58.000 --> 23:00.000
revolution in China.

23:00.000 --> 23:02.000
The next theory is

23:02.000 --> 23:04.000
very popular recently,

23:04.000 --> 23:06.000
but it is a bit similar

23:06.000 --> 23:08.000
to the idea of a national state.

23:08.000 --> 23:10.000
Historians believe that

23:10.000 --> 23:12.000
the people's historical memory

23:12.000 --> 23:14.000
should not serve the country.

23:14.000 --> 23:16.000
Therefore,

23:16.000 --> 23:18.000
historians began to write

23:18.000 --> 23:20.000
some important historical memories.

23:20.000 --> 23:22.000
For example,

23:22.000 --> 23:24.000
transitional justice should tell you

23:24.000 --> 23:26.000
that the Nazi massacre

23:26.000 --> 23:28.000
against the Jews

23:28.000 --> 23:30.000
was really horrible.

23:30.000 --> 23:32.000
We should remember this

23:32.000 --> 23:34.000
forever.

23:34.000 --> 23:36.000
Because it happened once,

23:36.000 --> 23:38.000
it may happen again.

23:38.000 --> 23:40.000
The main consciousness of Taiwan

23:40.000 --> 23:42.000
must be awakened,

23:42.000 --> 23:44.000
because the people of Taiwan

23:44.000 --> 23:46.000
have been oppressed for the past 400 years.

23:46.000 --> 23:48.000
These popular historical writings

23:48.000 --> 23:50.000
are actually shaping historical memory.

23:50.000 --> 23:52.000
Another group of people

23:52.000 --> 23:54.000
believe that

23:54.000 --> 23:56.000
history should not serve the country,

23:56.000 --> 23:58.000
so there are a lot of historical studies

23:58.000 --> 24:00.000
to deconstruct the national state.

24:00.000 --> 24:02.000
For example,

24:02.000 --> 24:04.000
tradition is invented,

24:04.000 --> 24:06.000
and tradition does not have

24:06.000 --> 24:08.000
a long history of 5,000 years.

24:08.000 --> 24:10.000
The so-called descendants of the King of Japan

24:10.000 --> 24:12.000
only appeared for 100 years.

24:12.000 --> 24:14.000
The so-called Japanese cuisine

24:14.000 --> 24:16.000
was invented after the Ming Dynasty.

24:16.000 --> 24:18.000
In the Middle Ages,

24:18.000 --> 24:20.000
the Emperor of Japan believed in Buddhism,

24:20.000 --> 24:22.000
so he told everyone not to eat meat.

24:22.000 --> 24:24.000
In ancient East Asia,

24:24.000 --> 24:26.000
there were four categories of animals

24:26.000 --> 24:28.000
in the world,

24:28.000 --> 24:30.000
such as grass fish and birds.

24:30.000 --> 24:32.000
At that time,

24:32.000 --> 24:34.000
the Emperor of Japan said

24:34.000 --> 24:36.000
that everyone was not allowed to eat meat,

24:36.000 --> 24:38.000
grass fish and birds.

24:38.000 --> 24:40.000
In fact,

24:40.000 --> 24:42.000
before the Ming Dynasty,

24:42.000 --> 24:44.000
the Japanese did not eat beef or pork,

24:44.000 --> 24:46.000
so the so-called barbecue and fried pork chops

24:46.000 --> 24:48.000
were far-fetched Japanese cuisine.

24:48.000 --> 24:50.000
They appeared in the late 19th century

24:50.000 --> 24:52.000
and even in the early 20th century.

24:53.000 --> 24:55.000
Finally, I think history

24:55.000 --> 24:57.000
is different from everyone else.

24:57.000 --> 24:59.000
In politics and sociology,

24:59.000 --> 25:01.000
they ask more objective questions,

25:01.000 --> 25:03.000
but in history,

25:03.000 --> 25:05.000
they also ask subjective questions.

25:05.000 --> 25:07.000
Traditional sociology

25:07.000 --> 25:09.000
may ask a question,

25:09.000 --> 25:11.000
such as

25:11.000 --> 25:13.000
whether the exam system

25:13.000 --> 25:15.000
has promoted social movement.

25:15.000 --> 25:17.000
So some historical sociologists

25:17.000 --> 25:19.000
will look for a lot of past history

25:19.000 --> 25:21.000
to see if there are some

25:21.000 --> 25:23.000
poor and hard-working people

25:23.000 --> 25:25.000
who became good officials

25:25.000 --> 25:27.000
because of the imperial examination,

25:27.000 --> 25:29.000
and then flew to Tengda

25:29.000 --> 25:31.000
and became famous

25:31.000 --> 25:33.000
from the Han dynasty.

25:33.000 --> 25:35.000
But historical sociology

25:35.000 --> 25:37.000
will ask a question.

25:37.000 --> 25:39.000
Objectively,

25:39.000 --> 25:41.000
even if the imperial examination

25:41.000 --> 25:43.000
really promoted social movement,

25:43.000 --> 25:45.000
did the people at that time

25:45.000 --> 25:47.000
really realize that

25:47.000 --> 25:49.000
the imperial examination

25:49.000 --> 25:51.000
promoted social movement?

25:51.000 --> 25:53.000
In the Han dynasty,

25:53.000 --> 25:55.000
there were some economic works.

25:55.000 --> 25:57.000
We can find out from economics

25:57.000 --> 25:59.000
what is the meaning of

25:59.000 --> 26:01.000
Chou Chou's The Theory of Economics?

26:01.000 --> 26:03.000
What does it mean in economics?

26:03.000 --> 26:05.000
But historians may ask

26:05.000 --> 26:07.000
a person who has not studied

26:07.000 --> 26:09.000
modern economics,

26:09.000 --> 26:11.000
has not studied Adam Smith,

26:11.000 --> 26:13.000
or has not studied economics

26:13.000 --> 26:15.000
in NTU,

26:15.000 --> 26:17.000
how can he write The Theory of Economics?

26:17.000 --> 26:19.000
I think this is the difference

26:19.000 --> 26:21.000
between historical sociology

26:21.000 --> 26:23.000
and other subjects.

26:23.000 --> 26:25.000
The next question is

26:25.000 --> 26:27.000
what is legal history?

26:27.000 --> 26:29.000
Why is legal history

26:29.000 --> 26:31.000
a field worth studying

26:31.000 --> 26:33.000
for me?

26:33.000 --> 26:35.000
The first argument is,

26:35.000 --> 26:37.000
of course,

26:37.000 --> 26:39.000
all the legal experts in the court

26:39.000 --> 26:41.000
are historians,

26:41.000 --> 26:43.000
because the court can only

26:43.000 --> 26:45.000
judge what has happened.

26:45.000 --> 26:47.000
I am going to discuss

26:47.000 --> 26:49.000
whether Su Jianhe killed someone

26:49.000 --> 26:51.000
in the past or not.

26:51.000 --> 26:53.000
Is he guilty or not?

26:53.000 --> 26:55.000
We can only discuss

26:55.000 --> 26:57.000
whether he killed someone in the past.

26:57.000 --> 26:59.000
The court cannot decide

26:59.000 --> 27:01.000
whether he will kill someone in the future.

27:01.000 --> 27:03.000
This is a matter of fact.

27:03.000 --> 27:05.000
The court can only deal with

27:05.000 --> 27:07.000
what has happened.

27:07.000 --> 27:09.000
From the legal point of view,

27:09.000 --> 27:11.000
when we make a judgment,

27:11.000 --> 27:13.000
the court will always

27:13.000 --> 27:15.000
make a judgment.

27:15.000 --> 27:17.000
In the tradition of British and American law,

27:17.000 --> 27:19.000
there are many cases

27:19.000 --> 27:21.000
that are not in the text,

27:21.000 --> 27:23.000
so you have to tell everyone

27:23.000 --> 27:25.000
whether the case in front of you

27:25.000 --> 27:27.000
is the same as the case in the past.

27:27.000 --> 27:29.000
If it is the same,

27:29.000 --> 27:31.000
you should apply the same law.

27:31.000 --> 27:33.000
If it is different,

27:33.000 --> 27:35.000
you should make another explanation.

27:35.000 --> 27:37.000
There are some famous cases

27:37.000 --> 27:39.000
where, for example,

27:39.000 --> 27:41.000
a court said that

27:41.000 --> 27:43.000
A car must pay

27:43.000 --> 27:45.000
$10,000.

27:45.000 --> 27:47.000
Later,

27:47.000 --> 27:49.000
a new case came out

27:49.000 --> 27:51.000
